Science of The Total Environment

Volume 861, 25 February 2023, 160678

Mobilization of colloids during sediment resuspension and its effect on the release of heavy metals and dissolved organic matter

Author links open overlay panel, , , ,
https://doi.org/10.1016/j.scitotenv.2022.160678Get rights and content

Highlights

  • â€¢

    Resuspension promoted mobilization and aggregation of colloids.

  • â€¢

    Aggregation of colloids formed particles and removed dissolved metals and DOM.

  • â€¢

    Mobilization of colloids could occur during the re-sedimentation process.

Abstract

Natural colloids are important in mobilizing pollutants in aquatic environments. This study investigated the mobilization and aggregation of natural colloids during the sediment resuspension and re-sedimentation processes using nanoparticle tracking analysis. The metals and organic matter in overlying water were divided and examined in dissolved (<0.45 Î¼m), colloidal (3 kDa â€“ 0.45 Î¼m), and truly dissolved (<3 kDa) forms. Excitation emission matrixâˆ’parallel factor analysis (EEM-PARAFAC) was used to characterize the dissolved organic matter (DOM). In overlying water, most natural colloids were < 200 nm before resuspension. An evident mobilization of colloids and an increase in colloid size were observed during resuspension. The formation of particles (>0.45 Î¼m) and decreases of small colloids (<200 nm) indicated that resuspension promoted the aggregation of colloids. Mobilization of colloids was accompanied by increases in concentrations of Fe, Al, and organic carbon in colloidal fractions, which could be related to the formation of mineral-organic complexes under an oxic environment. The release of DOM from sediments mainly contributed to the truly dissolved humic-like fraction, and colloidal organic carbon accounted for, on average, 20 % of the total dissolved organic carbon (DOC). Fe and Al had the highest colloidal proportions as they are major compositions of inorganic colloids. Substantial removal of dissolved Al, Fe, Pb, and Zn occurred when colloids aggregated in the overlying water. Although the adsorption of suspended particles may also decrease the concentrations of dissolved metals, the increased proportions of colloidal metals indicated a possible role of colloids in this process. These findings provide insight into the behavior of colloids during the resuspension process and indicate that the aggregation of colloids could promote the removal of dissolved matter.

1. Introduction

Metal contamination in aquatic systems has become an important environmental issue owing to rapidly expanding economic and industrial development (Liu et al., 2019; Wu et al., 2020a). Heavy metals do not degrade over time and can accumulate in organisms, posing a serious threat to ecosystems and human health. In shallow lakes, sediments serve as sinks for heavy metals from river flows and wastewater discharges (Eggleton and Thomas, 2004; Morgan et al., 2012; Xie et al., 2019). The buried heavy metals in sediments can be released into the overlying water through resuspension and gradient diffusion, which act as a long-term exposure source to ecosystems. Previous studies have focused on the release of heavy metals from sediments during the resuspension process and have investigated the effects of several factors, such as velocity, redox conditions, pH, ionic strength, and organic matter (Atkinson et al., 2007; Zhang et al., 2014). By changing the physical and chemical conditions of the sediment and overlying water, resuspension is important for regulating the distribution, mobility, and bioavailability of heavy metals in aquatic environments (De Jonge et al., 2012; Huo et al., 2015; Xie et al., 2019; Zhang et al., 2014). However, a thorough understanding of the dynamics of heavy metals during resuspension remains limited. For example, the patterns of concentrations of dissolved heavy metals are complex, both increase and decrease of metals are observed, depending on different kinds of metal and environmental factors (Wu et al., 2020a). In previous studies, heavy metals were usually separated into â€˜particulateâ€™ and â€˜dissolvedâ€™ forms with filtration membranes, where the boundary is somewhat arbitrarily dictated by the limited selection of available pore sizes, such as 0.45 Î¼m or 0.7 Î¼m. In reality, the heavy metals in â€˜dissolvedâ€™ form may not be truly dissolved. The ions adsorbed or bound by submicron particles and organic matter, which should have been called â€˜colloidal,â€™ were included in the â€˜dissolvedâ€™ phase in previous studies.

Natural colloids are a mixture of submicron particles and natural organic matter (NOM) that are ubiquitous in aquatic environments. Colloids are usually defined with a size range of 1 nm to 1 Î¼m; however, considering that 0.45 Î¼m filters are typically used to separate the water into particles and solutions, the boundary of the colloids has consequently been defined as 0.45 Î¼m in several studies (Cuss et al., 2020; Li et al., 2019; Xu et al., 2019). Owing to the small size, the surface of colloids is abundant in functional groups such as carboxyl, hydroxyl, and amino groups, which enables the strong adsorption and complexing ability of colloids with metal ions. Thus, colloidal heavy metals have been demonstrated to be an important component in dissolved metals. In a study of heavy metals in the Yellow Sea, colloidal Cd, Pb, and Cu accounted for 47â€“51 % of the total dissolved pool (Lu et al., 2019). Current research also focused on the fate of colloids in the real environment and the effect of colloids on pollutants under changes in environmental factors. For example, the presence of mobile kaolinite colloids could delay the adsorption of heavy metals to sand and facilitate the mobility of heavy metals in soils (Won et al., 2019). However, in the surface water environment, attention was mainly focused on the differences between colloids and colloidal pollutants on a large scale. The dynamic of colloids under a hydraulic environment is rarely studied, especially during the resuspension process. Resuspension is important for natural colloids in surface water. When sediments are dispersed during resuspension, a substantial mobilization of colloids will occur in the overlying water, accompanied by the release of pollutants from sediment. The mobilization of colloids and their effects on pollutants in this process is supposed to be influenced by many factors, including hydraulics, pH, ionic strength, redox reactions, and the presence of dissolved organic matter (DOM). Thus, for a comprehensive understanding of the fate of pollutants through the sediment-water interface, an investigation of the effects of colloids during resuspension is critical.

In this study, the mobilization and aggregation of colloids were investigated during the resuspension of lake sediments. Variations in metals (Al, Fe, Cu, Zn, Cd, Cr, Pb, and Ni) were measured in the colloidal (3 kDa â€“ 0.45 Î¼m), dissolved (<0.45 Î¼m), and truly dissolved fractions (<3 kDa). The concentrations of DOC and excitation-emission matrix (EEM) measurements, combined with PARAFAC analysis, were used to depict the dynamics of DOM. The objectives of this study were to (1) provide insight into the mobilization and aggregation behaviors of natural colloids during resuspension and (2) analyze the distribution and exchange of metals between different fractions and the role of colloids in this process.

2. Materials and methods

2.1. Sediment resuspension experiments

Surface sediments and water samples used in this study were collected from Meiliang Bay in Taihu Lake (31Â°24,895 â€²N, 120Â°02573â€² E) in October 2020. Taihu Lake is the third-largest freshwater lake in China and some areas have been recognized as heavily contaminated by Pb, Cd, Cr, and Cu (Rajeshkumar et al., 2018; Yang et al., 2020). The average water depth of Taihu Lake is 1.8 m and the lake is highly susceptible to resuspension due to disturbances from wind and dredge (Tang et al., 2020; Yang et al., 2020). When resuspension occurs, the organic matter and particles deposited in the sediment are released back into the overlying water, acting as sources of natural colloids in shallow lakes (Xu et al., 2018b).

A grab sampler was used to collect the surface sediment (0â€“10 cm depth) from the sampling sites. Water samples were collected 20 cm below the surface of the water and stored in sterilized polypropylene bottles, which were cleaned by soaking in 10 % HNO3 for 24 h and washed thoroughly with deionized water. After collection, all samples were transported to the laboratory and stored in the dark at 4 Â°C. The wet surface sediments were sieved through a 1 mm mesh to remove large-sized particles and impurities.

Sediment resuspension was simulated using a racetrack-style flume. The flume was equipped with a blower that can adjust the speed of the wind and stimulate wind-induced resuspension. The size of the flume was provided in Fig. S1. Sieved wet sediments were placed at the bottom of a flume and formed a 15 cm layer, and then unfiltered lake water was injected to form a 45 cm depth overlying water. The flume was kept away from direct sunlight and stood for 2 weeks to form a stable water-sediment interface. The pH values, dissolved oxygen (DO), and concentrations of dissolved metals and colloids were measured during this process to ensure a balance between sediments and water (Table. S1).

The sediment resuspension experiment contained an 8-h resuspension process and a 72-h sedimentation process. According to previous studies, the critical wind speed of sediment resuspension was 3.7â€“ 4.0 m/s in Taihu Lake, and the dominant wind speed ranged from 1.18 m/s to 6.98 m/s (You et al., 2007; Zheng et al., 2015). Thus, the speed of the wind was 4 m/s at the beginning of the stimulate experiment, increased with 1 m/s every hour, and kept at a speed of 8 m/s after 4 h. A siphon tube was used to collect the water sample and the position was fixed at a depth of almost 20 cm. When the wind-wave disturbance was exerted, water samples were collected at 0, 1, 2, 4, 6, and 8 h intervals. During the sedimentation process, water samples were collected at 2, 8, 24, and 72 h intervals (corresponding to 10, 16, 32, and 80 h from the beginning of disturbance) to completely simulate the resuspension process. Owing to the small proportion of water collected in the total water column in the flume (<1 %), the effects of water column changes were negligible. The pH, oxidation-reduction potential (ORP), and dissolved oxygen concentration were measured using portable meters (Hach, HQ14d). Water samples were immediately filtered through a pre-combusted 0.45 Î¼m mixed cellulose membrane filter to separate particles and solution, and the filtered water was stored in the dark at 4 Â°C for colloid separation and further analysis. To avoid possible blockage of filter membrane pores, each membrane filtered only 50 mL of water and a steady velocity of filtered flow is kept. Filter membranes were then dried at a temperature of 105 Â°C and then subtracted their original weight to measure the weights of suspended particles, and the collected particles were stored for further measurements.

2.2. Isolation of colloids

The natural colloids in this experiment were isolated using a method combined with ultrafiltration (UF) and dialysis. The UF membrane was previously cleaned by several recycling and flushing cycles using 0.05 N NaOH and 0.02 N HCl solution, followed by thorough flushing with purewater to prevent possible contamination from the apparatus. The 0.45 Î¼m-filtered water samples were first concentrated using a stirred ultrafiltration cell (Millipore, UFSCC01) with a 3 kDa membrane (Millipore, PLAC07619). The retentate flow was considered as the colloidal phase and the filtered flow was collected as the truly dissolved solution. A concentration factor of 10 was adopted to avoid the probable aggregation of colloids in the concentrated solution.

To avoid disturbance of truly dissolved matter in fluorescence spectra, dialysis was performed using a 3 kDa dialysis membrane (B0052, Viskase). Dialysis was performed following the method described by Kang et al. (2019). The 20 mL concentrated solution from ultrafiltration was placed in a dialysis bag and sealed using a dialysis clamp. The dialysis bag was then placed into a beaker containing purewater and stirred using a magnetic stirrer for 48 h with ultrapure water renewed every 12 h.

2.3. EEM measurements and PARAFAC analysis

The EEM measurements of the dissolved, colloidal, and truly dissolved solutions were performed using a Hitachi F-7000 spectrofluorometer. The concentrated colloid solutions were diluted to the original concentration with purewater before measurement. The absorption spectra of the samples were obtained by scanning the absorbance at wavelengths from 200 to 800 nm with a resolution of 1 nm using a UVâ€“visible spectrophotometer. Emission spectra of EEM were collected between 250 nm and 600 nm with 1 nm scan steps at excitation wavelengths ranging from 250 nm to 450 nm with 5 nm scan steps. The PMT voltage of the spectrophotometer was adjusted to 700 V, and the scan speed was set at 2400 nm/min.

The PARAFAC analysis was performed using the DOMFluor toolbox with MATLABR2019a. PARAFAC was computed using several component models with non-negativity constraints, and residual analysis, split-half analysis, and visual inspection were applied to determine the number of fluorescence components (Hu et al., 2019; Huang et al., 2018). Before analysis, Rayleigh and Raman scattering in the sample spectra were removed by subtracting the EEM of Milli-Q water according to the protocol described by Bahram et al. (2006). The fluorescence intensities were converted to quinine sulfate units (QSE), with 1 QSE equal to the fluorescence intensities at 350/450 nm (excitation/emission) of 1 Î¼g/L quinine sulfate in a 0.1 M H2SO4 solution. A detailed description of the PARAFAC analysis and EEM measurements is provided in our previous studies (Hu et al., 2019; Hu et al., 2017) and the Supporting Information (SI).

2.4. Analytical measurements

Concentrations of Al, Fe, Cu, Zn, Cr, Cd, Ni, and Pb in the dissolved (<0.45 Î¼m), truly dissolved (<3 kDa), colloidal (3 kDa â€“ 0.45 Î¼m), and particulate fractions (>0.45 Î¼m) were quantified using inductively coupled plasma mass spectrometry (ICP-MS; 7700X, Agilent). Before measuring, all water samples were digested with a mixed acid solution comprising HNO3, HCl, and H2O2 at a temperature of 180 Â°C for 15 min in a microwave digestion system (ETHOS A, Milestone). Suspended particles were dealt with a mixed acid solution comprising HNO3, HCl, and HF solution, followed by the digestion process in the same microwave digestion system. The linear calibration curves were constructed by analyzing the target metals in 5 % nitric acid ranging from 1 to 100 Î¼g/L. Certified reference samples were used to ensure the accuracy of the analysis and the recovery rate was 97.1 Â± 11.4 %. Concentrations of organic carbon in different fractions were measured by a high-temperature CO2 evolution method using a TOC analyzer (XPERT, Trace Elemental).

The numbers and size distributions of the natural colloids were characterized via nanoparticle tracking analysis (NTA) using a Nanosight NS300 (Malvern Instruments) equipped with a high-resolution CMOS camera and a standard red laser. The NTA could track the Brownian motion of different nanoparticles and calculate their numbers and sizes when the nanoparticles are irradiated by the laser. The analysis and methods used in this study followed those described by Hou et al. (2018) and detailed information was also provided in Supporting Information. To obtain real-time information on colloids, the samples used for NTA were waters that were filtered through a 0.45 Î¼m membrane, instead of the concentrated colloid solutions from the ultrafiltration system. The blockage and real cut-off size of the 0.45 Î¼m filter membrane were also analyzed with NTA by comparing the differences between a 0.7 Î¼m glass fiber membrane filtered water and the 0.45 Î¼m membrane filtered water. All measurements were repeated six times for each sample with fixed parameters (camera level, threshold detection, and screen gain; detailed information of parameters is reported in SI), and were finished within 10 min after the water samples were collected. The NTA 3.4 software was used to analyze the concentrations and sizes of colloids.

3. Results and discussion

3.1. Physicochemical characteristics of overlying water

The properties of the overlying water are shown in Fig. 1. During the resuspension process, the average values of pH ranged from 8.54 to 7.98, exhibiting an evident decrease when resuspension occurred. After resuspension, the low pH values persisted for 8 h and then slowly returned to 8.30. In anoxic environments, sediments usually contain a large number of reductive matter. The precipitation of hydroxides and the oxidation of reductive matters, such as sulfides, could release hydrogen ions into overlying water and cause measurable decreases in pH during resuspension (De Jonge et al., 2012; Morgan et al., 2012). In addition, the release of DOM from sediments could also bring a decrease in pH values, as important roles of humic and fulvic acid in DOM. Wind-induced resuspension resulted in an increase in DO concentration in overlying water, which increased from 7.56 mg/L to 8.22 mg/L in the first 4 h and slightly decreased when a high concentration of sediment was detected in the overlying water. After resuspension, higher concentrations of DO were detected in the overlying water when the sedimentation of sediments was complete. The ORP decreased from 203 mV to 168 mV in the first 2 h of resuspension and then kept growing until the end of resuspension. The differences between DO concentrations and ORP indicated that the redox environment in the overlying water was not only affected by the loading of oxygen from the wind disturbance but also by the concentrations of reductive matter that were suspended during the resuspension process.

The concentrations of suspended particulate matter (SPM) were considerably impacted by disturbance, which increased to 558â€“654 mg/L in the first 4 h and then reached a maximum value of 1009 mg/L. After resuspension, the residence time of SPM in the overlying water was approximately 8 h, and most SPM settled within 24 h. The resuspension process in this study was divided into two periods. In the first period, SPM mainly comprised surface particles that were easy to suspend, with concentrations ranging from 558 to 664 mg/L. Higher SPM concentrations were observed in the next period owing to a break in the water-sediment interface, which allowed the release of more sediments into the overlying water.

3.2. Mobilization and aggregation of colloids

The mobilization of colloids has been widely observed in water systems, especially in groundwater. Perturbations in physicochemical conditions (e.g., flow velocity, particle size, ionic strength and composition, pH, and ligands) have been recognized to affect the aggregation and remobilization of colloids (He et al., 2019; Liao et al., 2016). However, the occurrence of colloids has mostly been investigated in porous media, where colloids are influenced by the effects of deposition and clogging, and the fate of natural colloids in the surface water is poorly studied.

In this study, the numbers and sizes of colloids during the entire experiment were measured using NTA (NS300). The size given by NTA is hydrodynamic size. Although the hydrodynamic size is not equal to the real size of particles, several studies have reported that the hydrodynamic size measured by the particle-tracking approaches such as dynamic light scattering (DLS) and nanoparticle tracking analysis (NTA) is not significantly different from the actuality and has been widely used in colloids and nanomaterial research (Hou et al., 2018; Ribeiro et al., 2018; Wang et al., 2019). Comparing the differences between water samples filtered through 0.7 Î¼m membrane and 0.45 Î¼m membrane, real cut-off sizes of the 0.45 Î¼m membrane ranged from 400 nm to 450 nm in this experiment (Fig. S5). To clearly describe the characterization and aggregation of colloids, colloids were divided into small colloids (<200 nm), middle colloids (>200 nm and < 450 nm), and large colloids (>450 nm). The size boundary between small colloids and middle colloids was determined by the results of several measurements for undisturbed overlying water, which showed that 90 % of colloids in undisturbed water were below 200 nm in size. Remarkably, although the sample water measured in NTA was filtered through a 0.45 Î¼m membrane, particles with a size over 450 nm were still examined in solution owing to the aggregation of colloids. These particles were named â€˜large colloids,â€™ and their amounts could act as indicators of colloid aggregation. An additional experiment was conducted to confirm the aggregation of colloids during resuspension, and detailed information was provided in the Supporting information. Briefly, the 0.45 Î¼m filtered water samples were settled and stirred for 2 h respectively. Compared with the original filtered water, increases in average size and numbers of large colloids were found in both settled and stirred samples, indicating that colloids could aggregate under a hydraulic environment (Fig. S5).

Before resuspension, the concentration of colloids was 2.27 Ã— 108 particles/mL, and the concentrations for small, middle, and large colloids were 1.99 Ã— 108, 2.7 Ã— 107, and 9.74 Ã— 105 particles/mL (Fig. 2). Most colloids in the undisturbed water were identified as small colloids. When the disturbance started, a substantial increase in middle colloids was observed, which grew from 2.7 Ã— 107 to 1.82 Ã— 108 particles/mL within 2 h. However, the concentrations of small colloids decreased throughout the resuspension process, from 2.27 Ã— 108 to 8.19 Ã— 107 particles/mL. Hydrodynamic force during resuspension could shatter the unconsolidated particles into colloids and remobilize the colloids settled in sediments. The hydrodynamic force also provided a collision-prone environment that promoted the rapid formation of small colloids into larger colloids. According to the DLVO theory, smaller colloids usually have a weaker energy barrier, which allows easier aggregation behavior (Kanti Sen and Khilar, 2006; Kim, 2021). As a result, resuspension brought a large number of middle colloids into the overlying water, which accounted for 60 % of the total colloids after 4 h of disturbance. The large colloids maintained a low concentration in the early stages of resuspension (9.74 Ã— 105 particles/mL) and their percentage was <1 %. The concentration of large colloids grew to 3.95 Ã— 107 particles/mL after 4 h of resuspension. Combined with the decrease in the concentration of small colloids, a strong aggregation of colloids was confirmed in the overlying water after the beginning of resuspension. After 8 h of resuspension, the concentrations of colloids decreased, especially in the middle and large colloids. This phenomenon may be explained by the sedimentation of colloids caused by aggregation, wherein most colloids were aggregated into larger sizes and were easy to settle.

Remarkably, as the resuspension was completed, another mobilization of colloids was observed after 8 h of sedimentation. In contrast to the mobilization with disturbance, the number of small colloids showed an increase rather than a decrease, whereas the increases in the number of medium colloids were not evident. The mobilization of small colloids is probably caused by the formation of the mineral-organic complex. During resuspension, the downward transport of O2 and suspended reductive sediments resulted in a limited DO concentration in the overlying water. As a new sediment-water interface formed after resuspension, surficial sediments and retained suspended particles were exposed to a more oxidized environment, where the metal ions from sediments were susceptible to oxide formation. Several studies have reported the formation of mineral-organic colloids on oxic-anoxic surfaces (Li et al., 2019; Liao et al., 2017; Liao et al., 2020). For example, the size of Fe-NOM colloids is 1â€“3 nm under anoxic conditions and increases to >200 nm under oxic conditions. (Liao et al., 2017). In this study, the concentrations of colloidal organic carbon, colloidal Fe, and colloidal Al increased after resuspension (which will be discussed in the following sections), indicating a formation of mineral-NOM colloids in the overlying water. The differences also indicated that part middle colloids during resuspension were directly derived by hydrodynamic force through shattering the unconsolidated particles and remobilizing the colloids settled from sediments. This finding emphasizes that the chemical condition variation and hydrodynamic force are both important for the mobilization of natural colloids.

3.3. PARAFAC component characteristics

EEMs coupled with PARAFAC analysis were used to characterize the variations and distributions of the fluorescent dissolved organic matter (FDOM) in the dissolved and colloidal fractions. Four fluorescent components were identified based on PARAFAC analysis: two humic-like components (C1 and C2) and two protein-like components (C3 and C4). The fingerprint maps and spectral loadings of the four components are shown in Fig. 3.

All components were compared with the OpenFluor database with a Tucker congruence coefficient of up to 0.97 to verify their properties and sources. C1 was characterized by an excitation peak at 360 nm and an emission peak at 475 nm, which could be identified as terrestrial humic-like DOM from natural and agricultural catchments (Kulkarni et al., 2018; Shutova et al., 2014). C2 had a peak at Ex/Em = 310/420 nm and represented humic-like DOM derived from biological/microbial activity (Yan et al., 2020). C3 (Ex/Em = 275/330) was classified as a mixture of protein-like substances, such as tyrosine, amino acids (tryptophan), and phenolic moieties (Derrien et al., 2020). C4 (Ex/Em = 305/338) had fluorescence characteristics similar to those of tyrosine-like materials derived from autochthonous processes (Amaral et al., 2016).

Among the four PARAFAC components, humic-like components C1 and C2 had higher fluorescence intensities in the truly dissolved fractions. The average intensities of C1 and C2 in the truly dissolved fraction were 28.08 QSE and 38.83 QSE, respectively, while their intensities in the colloidal fraction were 12.7 QSE and 14.49 QSE, respectively. Higher proportions of C1 and C2 were also found in the truly dissolved fraction, suggesting that humic-like components are the main constituents of FDOM in the truly dissolved fraction. For protein-like components, a maximum percentage of C3 and a minimum percentage of C4 were found in the colloidal fraction, whereas the opposite was true for the truly dissolved fraction. The difference indicated that C3 had a higher molecular weight and was mainly distributed in colloids, whereas C4 had low molecular weight and soluble proteins.

3.4. Variations of organic matter in different fractions

In this study, variations of dissolved organic matter were divided into the dissolved fraction (<0.45 Î¼m), colloidal fraction (from 3 kDa to 0.45 Î¼m), and truly dissolved fraction (<3 kDa). The concentrations of their organic carbon content were designated â€˜DOCâ€™, â€˜COCâ€™, and â€˜TDOCâ€™. Owing to the strong disturbance and abundant reserves of NOM in Taihu Lake sediments, average concentrations of DOC in the overlying water showed dramatic variations during the experiment (Fig. 4), increasing from 14.18 mg/L to a maximum of 46.84 mg/L in 4 h and then gradually declining, although the disturbance continued for the next 4 h.

Before resuspension, the average COC concentration was 2.11 mg/L, accounting for 16 % of the dissolved concentration. During the resuspension process, the COC concentration increased to 4.81 mg/L, but the COC percentage remained low owing to a substantial increase in DOC. In contrast, average concentrations of TDOC increased from 10.97 mg/L to 42.31 mg/L, accounting for 82 %, on average. This distribution was consistent with a previous report that 67 % of bulk dissolved organic carbon (DOC) was partitioned in the <1 kDa molecular weight fraction (Xu et al., 2018a). However, when the resuspension process was completed, the COC concentration gradually increased to 6.97 mg/L and the percentage of COC increased to 37 %, whereas no increase in TDOC was observed. The concentrations of COC exhibited a positive correlation with concentrations of colloids (r = 0.83, p < 0.05), indicating most COC was comprised of the organic matter bound to the inorganic colloids.

FDOM exhibited a complicated distribution and changes in the colloidal, dissolved, and truly dissolved fractions (Fig. 5). Before resuspension, the total fluorescence intensity of the colloidal fraction was 51.22 QSE, whereas that of the truly dissolved fraction was 101.30 QSE, indicating that the majority of the FDOM was also distributed in the <3 kDa molecular weight fraction.

During the resuspension process, the total fluorescence intensity of the dissolved fraction increased from 177.47 QSE to 211.53 QSE in the first 6 h and then decreased to 168.92 QSE at the end of the experiment. This trend indicated a release effect of FDOM during the resuspension process, whereas the removal of FDOM during the sedimentation process could be attributed to adsorption and oxidation in the overlying water. However, compared with the concentrations of DOC, the variations in FDOM were slight, indicating an important role of non-fluorescent substances in the fate of OM.

The intensities of two humic-like components (C1 and C2) increased during resuspension and then decreased in the following sedimentation process, which was similar to that of the total fluorescence intensity. Humic-like components are the main constituents of sediment NOM, and their abundance usually increases under hypoxic conditions. The increase in humic-like components during resuspension contributed to their release from the sediments. However, the intensities of the protein-like components C3 and C4 decreased dramatically during the resuspension process and then recovered during sedimentation.

Differences in the components were also found between the colloidal and truly dissolved fractions. In the colloidal fraction, the intensities of the two humic-like components remained almost stable throughout the entire experiment, whereas in the truly dissolved fraction, their intensities continued to increase during the resuspension process. Combined with the distribution of humic-like components, the major role of the truly dissolved fraction could be confirmed in variations of humic-like matter. For protein-like components, the intensities of colloidal C3 and C4 decreased substantially during resuspension, which may have contributed to the aggregation of colloids during resuspension. The removal of DOM has been widely associated with its co-precipitation with colloids. DOM is usually negatively charged in a water environment and can adsorb onto most colloids such as iron oxide, aluminum oxide, and kaolinite, which is considered an important transformation from DOM to POM (Drozdova et al., 2020; Oleinikova et al., 2019; Philippe and Schaumann, 2014). In addition, water conditions during resuspension, such as bubbles generated from water turbulence and the oxidation environment, can promote the self-flocculation phenomenon of DOM (He et al., 2016).

3.5. Dynamics of metals in different fractions

Eight metals, including Al, Fe, Cu, Pb, Cr, Cd, Ni, and Zn, were examined in this study, which accounted for the metal contamination in Taihu Lake. To avoid inaccuracies caused by low concentrations of SPM, concentrations of metals in SPM were only measured after 1 h of resuspension and before 8 h of sedimentation.

As shown in Fig. 6, the range of the concentrations of particulate Cu, Pb, Cr, Cd, Ni, and Zn were 24.85 Â± 7.56â€“ 315.92 Â± 9.88 Î¼g/g, 25.65 Â± 1.2â€“ 30.67 Â± 2.2 Î¼g/g, 85.25 Â± 2.65â€“ 119.60 Â± 7.56 Î¼g/g, 0.62 Â± 0.1â€“ 1.04 Â± 0.15 Î¼g/g, 56.02 Â± 2.75â€“ 77.04 Â± 2.58 Î¼g/g, and 95.8 Â± 5.61â€“ 161.2 Â± 8.47 Î¼g/g, respectively. These results were of the same order as the concentrations of particulate metals reported in previous studies (Yang et al., 2020; Zheng et al., 2013). Al and Fe were present in much higher concentrations in SPM than those of other metals, as they are important constituent minerals of the particles. During resuspension, most metal concentrations in SPM decreased after 2 h of disturbance, which could be attributed to the continuous suspension of the coarse particles from deeper sediments. Concentrations of metals in SPM were found to be negatively correlated with their size owing to the disadvantage of coarse particles in the surface area (Huang et al., 2012). In the early stage of resuspension, particles of small size were easier to suspend and brought higher concentrations of metals in the particles. The addition of coarse particles in overlying water could result in a decrease in metal concentrations in total particles. In addition, the finer particles are also reported to contain a high concentration of POM (particulate organic matter), which would promote their binding affinities with metals (Chen et al., 2018; Wu et al., 2020b). In this experiment, a marked increase in SPM between 4 h and 6 h indicated a break in the sediment-water interface, which allowed the release of coarse particles with less metal contamination. After resuspension, recovery of particulate metal concentrations was observed because of the quick sedimentation of coarse particles in the overlying water and fresh particles formed by the aggregation of colloids, which we discuss in the following sections.

In this study, the concentrations of the dissolved metals were divided into colloidal and truly dissolved fractions, and their values are shown in Fig. 7. As no evident decreases in the numbers of colloids (Fig. 2) and concentrations of colloidal metal (Fig. 7) were observed during resuspension, the blockages of filter membrane were not significant and the decreases in dissolved metal were not caused by the retention of the membrane.

Al and Fe are the major constituents of colloids. According to our results, the highest percentages of colloidal fractions were found for Al and Fe, ranging from 54 % to 83 % for Al and 33 % to 76 % for Fe. A part of the increased colloidal Al and Fe can be attributed to the dispersion of small clay, as the natural inorganic colloids in Taihu Lake contain montmorillonite, nontronite, and volkonskoite (Xu et al., 2018b). Variations in chemistry properties during resuspension also have an effect. In the aquatic environment, the Al could form hydroxides, and insoluble Al(OH)3 dominates at pH 6â€“9 (Egemose et al., 2009; NamieÅ›nik and Rabajczyk, 2010). In this experiment, the pH of overlying water ranged from 8.54 to 7.98, and the colloidal Al contributed to the increase of Al during resuspension. Speciation of Fe is sensitive to redox conditions, and Fe (hydr)oxides could reductively dissolve in sediment, owing to lack of oxygen and microbial reduction (Bishop et al., 2019). In this experiment, the concentrations of colloidal Al and Fe were closely related to concentrations of DO and colloids (r = 0.85, 0.7, 0.85, 0.76 respectively, p < 0.05, details in Fig. S4), which indicated an important role of oxygen in the dynamics of colloidal Al and Fe. After 2 h of resuspension, both concentrations of dissolved Al and Fe decreased until the end of resuspension. An evident aggregation of colloids was also observed after 2 h of resuspension; the decreases of dissolved Fe and Al could be explained by the oxidation which increased their (hydr)oxides in colloidal fraction and then aggregated to form particles. In this experiment, the concentrations of colloidal Al increased from 181.07 to 292.87 Î¼g/L and the concentrations of Fe increased from 140.18 to 301.83 Î¼g/L. In contrast, the concentrations of Al and Fe in the truly dissolved fraction decreased substantially after 2 h, resulting in higher proportions of colloidal fractions.

The concentrations of Pb, Cd and Zn in the dissolved fraction increased after a short period of resuspension and were effectively removed from the dissolved fraction before the end of the resuspension. However, unlike Al and Fe, the concentrations of colloidal Pb, Cd, and Zn were relatively low, and the truly dissolved fractions accounted for higher percentages in the dissolved pool. The evident variations in truly dissolved concentrations indicate the more important roles of metal ions and metals bound to low molecular weight DOM. Remarkably, the duration of high concentrations of truly dissolved Pb, and Zn were short during resuspension, as oxidation and adsorption effects could effectively remove metals from the dissolved phase. Previous studies also reported quick re-absorption of Pb and Zn to particles upon oxidation (Eggleton and Thomas, 2004). A limited role of colloids was also suggested for these metals owing to the decrease in colloidal concentrations of Pb, Cd, and Zn during resuspension.

No evident releases of the dissolved Cu and Cr were found throughout the whole resuspension process. The decrease in dissolved Cu caused by resuspension has been reported in several studies and was related to adsorption from suspended solids and cyanobacteria (Wu et al., 2020a). Another study attributed the decrease in dissolved Cu to the very low solubility of CuS (Xu et al., 2015). Cr has the potential to be oxidized from Cr(III) to Cr(VI), which substantially increases its concentration in the soluble phase. However, several studies have also emphasized that the reaction kinetics associated with the oxidation of Cr(III) to Cr(VI) are unfavorable (Magar et al., 2008; Xu et al., 2017). Fe(II) or DOM can also chemically reduce Cr(VI) to Cr(III) and formed Cr(III)-Fe(III)-OM colloids under an oxic condition; >90 % of Cr(III) is found in form of colloid when the concentration of humic acid exceeds 10 mg C/L (Liao et al., 2020). In this experiment, the large amount of Fe and DOM released from the reductive sediment probably prevented the formation of soluble Cr(VI) in the overlying water, and the Cr is incorporated into the colloids.

After resuspension, the concentrations of most metals recovered, mainly contributing to the variations in truly dissolved fractions. In this process, a new sediment-water interface was formed and suspended particles were retained in the overlying water. Owing to the higher DO concentration in the overlying water, the desorption of metals was promoted by the oxidation of sulfides in sediment and particles. Thus, increasing oxygen concentrations can enhance the mobility of trace metals, which may result in the leaching of sediment-bound metals into the overlying surface water, even in undisturbed water (De Jonge et al., 2012).

In general, most metals in this study showed decreases in their dissolved concentrations when aggregation of colloids occurred in the overlying water, except Ni. The decreases were mainly attributed to variations in the concentrations of truly dissolved metal, while the concentrations of most colloidal metals remained relatively stable, which resulted in higher proportions of colloidal metals. These findings indicate a close relationship between colloid aggregation and the removal of dissolved metals. However, the increases in particulate metals were not found when colloids aggregation as the number of metals in the dissolved fraction is much less than those in the particles. During resuspension, it is reported that the numbers of heavy metals in particles may be one to two orders of magnitude higher than those in dissolved fractions (Buyang et al., 2019; Choppala et al., 2018). Thus, the removed metals from the dissolved fraction did not bring obvious increases in particulate metals. On the other side, because of substance exchanges between the overlying water and sediments, fluxes of heavy metals between dissolved, truly dissolved, and colloidal fractions could not be calculated in this experiment. The understanding of the contributions of colloid aggregation and SPM adsorption to the removal of heavy metals from overlying water remains limited and should be investigated in further studies.

4. Conclusions

To investigate the role of colloids in the release of heavy metals during the resuspension process, a wind-induced resuspension simulation experiment was conducted using contaminated sediments collected from Taihu Lake. A combined method of UF and dialysis was adopted for quick collection of colloids, and an NTA instrument was used to reveal the number and size distribution of the colloids. Dynamics of heavy metals were measured in â€˜dissolved,â€™ â€˜colloidal,â€™ and â€˜truly dissolvedâ€™ fractions, while information on DOM was characterized with excitation and emission matrix combined with parallel factor analysis. DOM and FDOM in the overlying water mainly comprised truly dissolved matter, whereas the colloidal fraction only accounted for 20 % of the total organic carbon on average. Resuspension significantly mobilized the middle (>200 nm, <450 nm) and large (>450 nm) colloids. The more frequent collisions caused by resuspension promoted the aggregation of colloids and the formation of particles, which were closely related to the decrease in dissolved heavy metals in the overlying water during resuspension. After resuspension, a different mechanism of small colloid mobilization was observed, which was probably owing to the formation of the mineral-DOM complex.
